g.text: Cache Line 0x000x27 (64B boundary struct fits entirely; 24B unused tail)

div.p: atomic.LoadInt32 / StoreInt32 Values: 0=Closed 1=Open 2=HalfOpen Read lock-free from State() for observability. Written under mu during transitions. Must be 4-byte aligned sits at 0x00.
Compiler-inserted padding Aligns the next int64 (failures) to 8-byte boundary required by sync/atomic on all platforms (arm32 ABI guarantee). Contains no meaningful data.

sync.Mutex protected (write) atomic.LoadInt64 safe (read) failures consecutive failure counter; reset to 0 on success or trip. windowStart UnixNano of first failure in current window; reset with failures. openUntil UnixNano deadline; when time.Now() > openUntil the circuit may probe (HalfOpen). All three are 8-byte aligned (0x08, 0x10, 0x18) satisfying atomic 64-bit access on 32-bit ARM.

sync.Mutex 8 bytes (two int32 fields) Protects: state transitions, failures, windowStart, openUntil, probeInFlight. Why mutex AND atomic? State() is called from observability code on every request must never block. All WRITES to state go through Allow() / RecordSuccess() / RecordFailure() which hold mu consistent view guaranteed. Atomic READ of state sees the last mu-protected write; no torn reads on aligned int32.
Total struct size: 40 bytes One 64-byte cache line 24 bytes unused unsafe.Sizeof(CircuitBreaker{}) == 40

Why this layout matters Allow() is on the critical path of every proxied request. Lock contention on mu stalls goroutines waiting to enter. Separating the READ path (atomic state) from the WRITE path (mutex for transitions) means 99.9 % of calls normal operation in Closed state do a single atomic load and return true without acquiring mu. The mutex is only contested during the rare failure Open and Open HalfOpen transitions, which happen at most once per 30-second window.
